  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Preface to Poems Sent to Jeong Dalga Upon His Embassy to Japan
  author: Lee Sunggin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fourth autumn, seventh month of the Regent's reign, the commander of Gyeongsang Province reported through a relay messenger that an envoy from Hae Fortress in Japan had arrived. The envoy said, "I come with wishes to present before the court. I humbly request that this be reported to the throne." The provincial commander, charged with the borders, dared not delay in doing so.

    When the matter was brought before the inner palace, the Regent replied, "Hae Fortress is a great garrison of Japan. That an envoy has come is no mere chance. Let the provinces provide sustenance and lodging along the route." When the envoy reached the capital, the Court of Tributary Relations presented him at the palace gates. The Regent's words of comfort were gracious and generous. After the envoy presented the state letter and gifts, he came forward to report: "My commander has heard of island pirates rising in rebellion, burning homes and destroying families. Growing both fierce and ashamed, he resolved to extinguish them utterly and has sent me to inform you of the time of our campaign."

    The Regent, upon hearing these words, approved all the more. He commanded the officials to provide provisions and elevated the envoy's rank. After lingering a month, when the envoy took his leave, the Regent summoned his ministers and said, "To respond to their embassy is a matter of courtesy. How much more so now, when we seek to strengthen bonds with our neighbor and end the scourge of brigandage. Our return envoy must be chosen with great care."

    Thus was Jeong Dalga, Grand Instructor of the National Academy, dispatched on this mission. His friends, both old and new, composed poems in his honor and asked me to write this preface.

    I reflect that Japan, having possessed a kingdom since ancient times, has maintained contact with the civilized world since the Han and Wei dynasties. Their robes and institutions shine brilliantly for all to see. Now the commander of Hae Fortress is a man of prowess and valor, a bulwark of his region, determined to suppress disorder and establish friendship between our two nations. Such resolve is worthy of praise.

    Dalga possesses learning that spans past and present, a character both refined and resolute, speech both gentle and clear. He has wandered through Wu and Chu, traversed the ancient lands of Qi and Lu, and bears something of the spirit of Sima Qian himself. To conduct diplomatic discourse on behalf of his sovereign is for him but a minor task. Yet in this world, some men hesitate even to cross their own threshold to visit neighboring villages. But Dalga, from the moment he received his commission, sprang forward with joy, taking it upon himself as his sacred duty, viewing the vast sea as though it were a smooth road before him. Truly, an ideal envoy has been found. One can already lift one's heels in anticipation that neighborly bonds will flourish and the scourge of brigandage will vanish.

    In days to come, the historian's brush will record with special emphasis: "The Japan Envoy, Jeong Dalga." Is this not a thing of greatness? And what follows will not be limited to great councils convened and great policies enacted—the historian's pen will flow again and again in commemoration. Let Dalga remember these words.
  footnotes:
    - 'Hae Fortress (霸家臺): A major fortress and administrative center in Japan during this period, representing Japanese authority and military power.'
    - 'Sima Qian (司馬子長): The renowned historian of the Western Han dynasty, author of the Records of the Grand Historian (史記), celebrated for both his historical scholarship and literary elegance.'
    - The reference to Jeong Mong-ju at the end suggests that Jeong Dalga may be another name or title for this historically significant figure, or that the author is invoking historical precedent.
    - 'Wu and Chu, Qi and Lu: Ancient Chinese regions and kingdoms, representing centers of classical learning and culture; Dalga''s travels through these lands indicate his deep engagement with Chinese intellectual traditions.'
